Scope and Nature of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) Audits
We have performed audits of the accompanying financial statements of Parker Defined Benefit Pension Plan (“the
Plan”), an employee benefit plan subject to the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (ERISA), as
permitted by ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C). The financial statements comprise the statements of net assets available
for benefits as of December 31, 2024 and 2023, and the related statements of changes in net assets available for
benefits for the years then ended, and the related notes to the financial statements.
Management, having determined it is permissible in the circumstances, has elected to have the audits of the Plan’s
financial statements performed in accordance with ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) pursuant to 29 CFR 2520.103-8 of
the Department of Labor’s Rules and Regulations for Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA. As permitted by
ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C), our audits need not extend to any statements or information related to assets held
for investment of the plan (investment information) by a bank or similar institution or insurance carrier that is
regulated, supervised, and subject to periodic examination by a state or federal agency, provided that the
statements or information regarding assets so held are prepared and certified to by the bank or similar institution
or insurance carrier in accordance with 29 CFR 2520.103-5 of the Department of Labor’s Rules and Regulations
for Reporting and Disclosure under ERISA (qualified institution).
Management has obtained certifications from qualified institutions as of December 31, 2024 and 2023, and the
years then ended, stating that the certified investment information, as described in Note 9 to the financial
statements, is complete and accurate.
Opinion
In our opinion, based on our audits and on the procedures performed as described in the Auditors’ Responsibilities
for the Audit of the Financial Statements section:
 the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements referred to above, other than those agreed to or
derived from the certified investment information, are presented fairly, in all material respects, in
accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.
 the information in the financial statements referred to above related to assets held by and certified to by a
qualified institution agrees to, or is derived from, in all material respects, the information prepared and
certified by an institution that management determined meets the requirements of ERISA Section
103(a)(3)(C).
Basis for Opinion
We conducted our audits in accordance with auditing standards generally accepted in the United States of America.
Our responsibilities under those standards are further described in the Auditors’ Responsibilities for the Audit of
the Financial Statements section of our report. We are required to be independent of the Plan and to meet our
other ethical responsibilities in accordance with the relevant ethical requirements relating to our audits. We believe
that the audit evidence we have obtained is sufficient and appropriate to provide a basis for our ERISA Section
103(a)(3)(C) audit opinion.

Responsibilities of Management for the Financial Statements
Management is responsible for the preparation and fair presentation of the financial statements in accordance with
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America, and for the design, implementation, and
maintenance of internal control relevant to the preparation and fair presentation of financial statements that are
free from material misstatement, whether due to fraud or error. Management’s election of the ERISA Section
103(a)(3)(C) audit does not affect management's responsibility for the financial statements.
In preparing the financial statements, management is required to evaluate whether there are conditions or events,
considered in the aggregate, that raise substantial doubt about the Plan’s ability to continue as a going concern
for one year after the date the financial statements are available to be issued.
Management is also responsible for maintaining a current plan instrument, including all plan amendments;
administering the plan; and determining that the plan’s transactions that are presented and disclosed in the
financial statements are in conformity with the plan's provisions, including maintaining sufficient records with
respect to each of the participants, to determine the benefits due or which may become due to such participants.
Auditors’ Responsibilities for the Audits of the Financial Statements
Except as described in the Scope and Nature of the ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) Audits section of our report, our
objectives are to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements as a whole are free from
material misstatement, whether due to fraud or error, and to issue an auditor’s report that includes our opinion.
Reasonable assurance is a high level of assurance but is not absolute assurance and therefore is not a guarantee
that an audit conducted in accordance with generally accepted auditing standards will always detect a material
misstatement when it exists. The risk of not detecting a material misstatement resulting from fraud is higher than
for one resulting from error, as fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional omissions, misrepresentations, or
the override of internal control. Misstatements are considered material if there is a substantial likelihood that,
individually or in the aggregate, they would influence the judgment made by a reasonable user based on the
financial statements.
In performing an audit in accordance with generally accepted auditing standards, we:
 Exercise professional judgment and maintain professional skepticism throughout the audits.
 Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due to fraud or
error, and design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks. Such procedures include
examining, on a test basis, evidence regarding the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements.
 Obtain an understanding of internal control relevant to the audits in order to design audit procedures that
are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness
of the Plan’s internal control. Accordingly, no such opinion is expressed.
 Evaluate the appropriateness of accounting policies used and the reasonableness of significant
accounting estimates made by management, as well as evaluate the overall presentation of the financial
statements.
 Conclude whether, in our judgment, there are conditions or events, considered in the aggregate, that raise
substantial doubt about the Plan’s ability to continue as a going concern for a reasonable period of time.
Our audits did not extend to the certified investment information, except for obtaining and reading the certification,
comparing the certified investment information with the related information presented and disclosed in the financial
statements, and reading the disclosures relating to the certified investment information to assess whether they are
in accordance with the presentation and disclosure requirements of accounting principles generally accepted in
the United States of America.
Accordingly, the objective of an ERISA Section 103(a)(3)(C) audit is not to express an opinion about whether the
financial statements as a whole are presented fairly, in all material respects, in accordance with accounting
principles generally accepted in the United States of America.

NOTE 1 – DESCRIPTION OF THE PLAN
The following description of the Parker Defined Benefit Pension Plan (the “Plan”) is provided for general
information purposes only. Participants should refer to the Plan document for more complete information.
The Plan is a noncontributory defined benefit pension plan covering hourly employees of Meggitt Aircraft
Braking Systems Corporation (“MABS”) who were employed prior to July 1, 2010, and Meggitt (Rockmart),
Inc. (“Rockmart”) (formerly Engineered Fabrics Corp.) who were employed prior to March 1, 2007. Terms of
employment for MABS and Rockmart hourly employees are covered by collective bargaining agreements.
MABS and Rockmart are wholly owned subsidiaries of Meggitt-USA, Inc (the Plan Sponsor). Effective
September 12, 2022, Parker-Hannifin Corporation (“Parker” or the “Company”) completed the acquisition of
Meggitt PLC (“Meggitt”), the parent company of Meggitt-USA, Inc. On May 1, 2023 the Plan was renamed
as the Parker Defined Benefit Pension Plan. The Plan is subject to the provisions of the Employee
Retirement Income Security Act of 1974, as amended (“ERISA”). On November 1, 2024, the Company
divested Rockmart resulting in covered Rockmart employees ceasing to accrue benefits under the Plan as
of the effective date of the divestiture.
Effective May 31, 2023, the Plan was amended to change the Plan Sponsor from Meggitt-USA, Inc. to
Parker and to merge the Whittaker Corporation Employees’ Pension Plan (“Whittaker Plan”), the K&F
Industries Retirement Plan for Salaried Employees’ (“Salaried Plan”), and the Parker-Hannifin Consolidated
Pension Plan-A (“CPP-A Plan”) into the Plan (collectively the “Merged Plans”). The Merged Plans were
other qualified noncontributory defined benefit plans sponsored by Meggitt-USA, Inc. or Parker. The assets,
liabilities, and all accrued benefits of the Merged Plans became assets, liabilities and accrued benefits
under the Parker Defined Benefit Pension Plan effective May 31, 2023 and all provisions in effect for the
Merged Plans continue to be applicable to determine any benefits payable. Below is a summary of the
assets transferred in from the Merged Plans effective May 31, 2023:
Whittaker Plan $ 65,225,276
Salaried Plan 89,953,451
CPP-A Plan 3 ,202,459,201
$ 3,357,637,928
The Company contributes such amounts as necessary, on an actuarial basis, to provide plan assets
sufficient to pay benefits to the Plan's participants. The normal retirement age is 65. The Plan also provides
for early retirement upon reaching established age and service levels, certain disability benefits, death
benefits and certain termination provisions. Participants should refer to the appropriate summary plan
description or the plan document for more complete information. The Plan is subject to the provisions of the
ERISA, as amended, the Pension Protection Act of 2006 (“PPA”), as amended and corrected, and the
Moving Ahead for Progress in the 21st Century Act (“MAP-21”).
Automatic participation in the Plan by new employees of the Company is restricted to certain employees.
Most new employees of the Company are automatically enrolled in a defined contribution plan in lieu of
their participation in the Plan. As a result of the Company's continual consolidation of its pension plans, a
majority of the Company's employees have frozen pension benefits in the Plan as well as ongoing
participation in the defined contribution plan.

NOTE 2 – SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES
Basis of Accounting
The accompanying financial statements are prepared on the accrual basis of accounting; however, benefit
payments are recorded when paid.
Investment Valuation and Income Recognition
Prior to May 31, 2023, the Plan’s sole investment was an interest in the K & F Industries Master Pension
Trust (“Master Trust”), which was established for the pooled investment of assets of the Plan and the
Salaried Plan. The Plan’s investment in the Master Trust was stated at fair value based on the fair value of
the net assets of the Master Trust. As part of the amendment disclosed in Note 1, the assets of the Plan
were transferred out of the Master Trust and into another trust, which states the assets at fair value. Fair
value is the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly
transaction between market participants at the measurement date. See Note 6 for a discussion of fair value
measurements.
Purchases and sales of securities are recorded on a trade-date basis. Interest income is recorded on the
accrual basis. Dividends are recorded on the ex-dividend date. Net income (loss) includes the Plan’s share
of gains and losses on investments bought and sold, as well as held by the Master Trust during the year.
Contributions
Company contributions meet the minimum funding requirements of ERISA, the PPA and MAP-21 and were
designed to fund the Plan's current service costs on a current basis and to fund the estimated accrued
benefit cost arising from qualifying past service over the applicable time period. There were no Company
contributions made during 2024 and 2023. No Company contributions were required to meet the required
minimum funding requirements of ERISA for 2024 and 2023.
Payment of Benefits
Benefit payments to participants are recorded upon distribution.
Expenses
The Plan’s expenses are paid either by the Plan or the Company, as provided by the plan document.
Expenses that are paid directly by the Company are excluded from these financial statements.
Risk and Uncertainties
The Plan invests in various investment securities. Investment securities are exposed to various risks such
as interest rate, market and credit risks. Due to the level of risk associated with certain investment
securities, it is at least reasonably possible that changes in the values of investment securities can occur
and that such change can materially affect the amounts reported in the statements of net assets available
for benefits.

NOTE 3 – ACTUARIAL PRESENT VALUE OF ACCUMULATED PLAN BENEFITS
Accumulated plan benefits were calculated by consulting actuaries at January 1, 2025, the most recent
benefit information date. Had the valuation been performed as of December 31, 2024, there would be no
material differences in the accumulated plan benefits. The valuation was performed using the Pri-2012
tables, projected using generational scale MP-2021. Generational scales are issued annually by the
Society of Actuaries. Accumulated plan benefits represent those future periodic payments, including lump-
sum distributions that are attributable under the Plan's provisions to the service employees have rendered
and include benefits expected to be paid to (a) retired or terminated employees or their beneficiaries, (b)
beneficiaries of employees who have died and (c) present employees or their beneficiaries. Benefits
payable under all circumstances (retirement, death, disability and termination of employment) are included
to the extent they are deemed attributable to employee service rendered prior to the valuation date. The
actuarial present value of accumulated plan benefits is the amount that results from applying actuarial
assumptions to adjust the accumulated plan benefits to reflect the time value of money (through discounts
for interest) and the probability of payment (by means of decrements such as for death, disability,
withdrawal or retirement) between the valuation date and the expected dates of payments.

NOTE 5 – FAIR VALUE MEASUREMENT
The framework for measuring fair value provides a fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to
valuation techniques used to measure fair value. The hierarchy gives the highest priority to unadjusted
quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities (Level 1 measurements) and the lowest
priority to unobservable inputs (Level 3 measurements). The three levels of the fair value hierarchy are
described as follows:
Level 1 – Inputs to the valuation methodology are unadjusted quoted prices for identical assets or liabilities
in active markets that the Plan has the ability to access.
Level 2 – Inputs other than quoted prices included within Level 1 that are observable for the asset or
liability, either directly or indirectly, such as:
– quoted prices for similar assets or liabilities in active markets;
– quoted prices for identical or similar assets or liabilities in inactive markets;
– inputs other than quoted prices that are observable for the asset or liability;
– inputs that are derived principally from or corroborated by observable market data by correlation or other
means.
If the asset or liability has a specified (contractual) term, the Level 2 input must be observable for
substantially the full term of the asset or liability.
Level 3 – Inputs to the valuation methodology are unobservable and significant to the fair value
measurement.
The asset or liability’s fair value measurement level within the fair value hierarchy is based on the lowest
level of any input that is significant to the fair value measurement. Valuation techniques maximize the use
of relevant observable inputs and minimize the use of unobservable inputs.

Following is a description of the valuation methodologies used for assets and liabilities measured at fair
value. There have been no changes in the methodologies used at December 31, 2024 and 2023.
Cash and cash equivalents are valued at cost, which approximates fair value. The Plan utilizes a liability-
hedging initiative requiring the Plan to maintain a certain cash balance. As of December 31, 2024 and
2023, the required cash balance totaled approximately $45 million and $48 million, respectively.
Equity securities consist solely of the Company's common shares and are valued at the closing price
reported on the active market on which the security is traded.
Government securities, corporate debt securities and real estate debt securities are valued using both
market observable inputs for similar assets that were traded on an active market and the closing price on
the active market on which the individual securities are traded.
Miscellaneous includes a long-term private placement investment which was measured at fair value using
observable inputs.
Investments measured at net asset value include commingled equity and fixed income funds and
alternatives at December 31, 2024. Investments measured at net asset value included non-exchange
traded mutual funds, common/collective trusts and limited partnerships at December 31, 2023. At
December 31, 2024 and 2023, the Plan had no unfunded commitments related to investments measured at
net asset value.
 Commingled equity and fixed income funds consist of common/collective trusts or other investment
vehicles. Commingled equity and fixed income funds have no redemption restrictions or lock-up
periods and can be liquidated within 90 days. As of December 31, 2024, there were
$1,657,619,158 in commingled equity and fixed income funds valued at net asset value per share.

December 31, 2024 and 2023
 Alternatives include investments in real estate, hedge funds, and private debt. Alternatives may be
subject to redemption restrictions, and valuations for certain real estate and private debt funds may
be lagged up to 6 months. As of December 31, 2024, there were $636,986,068 in alternatives
valued at net asset value per share.
 Non-exchange traded mutual funds consist primarily of fixed income securities available to
institutional clients. Non-exchange traded mutual funds can be redeemed daily and without
restriction. Redemption of a certain mutual fund is subject to a lock-up period, lasting throughout its
duration, scheduled to terminate July 2026. However, this mutual fund may extend its duration up
to additional two years under certain conditions. As of December 31, 2023, there were
$337,101,028 in non-exchange traded mutual funds valued at net asset value per share.
 Common/collective trusts primarily consist of equity, fixed income and real estate funds and
provide exposure to large, mid and small cap U.S. equities, international large and small cap
equities, emerging market equities, U.S., international and emerging market debt securities and
real estate funds. Common/collective trust investments can be redeemed after giving appropriate
notice to the issuer, generally, no more than a 90-day redemption notice. As of December 31,
2023, there were $1,546,313,939 in common/collective trusts valued at net asset value per share.
 A certain limited partnership investment is restricted to a maximum redemption of 20 percent of its
account balance every six months upon a 90-day notification period. As of December 31, 2023,
there were $113,948,444 in limited partnership investments valued at net asset value per share.
The Plan's investment strategy for equity securities and equity funds, within both the mutual fund and
common/collective trust asset class, is to obtain capital appreciation in an amount that at least equals
various market-based benchmarks. The primary investment objective of fixed income securities and fixed
income funds, within both the mutual fund and common/collective trust asset class, is to provide for a
constant stream of income while preserving capital. The primary investment objective of the investments in
the limited partnerships and miscellaneous category is to provide a stable rate of return over a specified
period of time.
NOTE 6 – DERIVATIVE INSTRUMENTS
The Plan invests in certain derivative instruments, which are transactions whose values depend on or are
derived from (in whole or in part) the value of one or more other assets, such as securities, currencies,
commodities, or indices. The Plan uses derivative instruments to mitigate certain investment risks, such as
interest rate risk and credit risk. The Plan records all derivatives at their fair value, which are included in
investments, at fair value on the Statements of Net Assets Available for Benefits and are recorded as
derivative instruments in the fair value table in Note 5.

Schedule SB, Part V — Summary of Plan Provisions
Meggitt Whittaker
Effective Date November 1, 1967. Amended and restated effective
January 1, 2014
Eligibility for Participation An employee shall become a participant in this plan upon
reaching age 21 and completing one year of service.
The plan is frozen to new hires after October 31, 1994.
Normal Retirement
Eligibility Age 65
Benefit A monthly amount equal to the sum of (1) + (2) but not
less than (3):
(1) 2.0% of Final Average Earnings minus 1.5% of the
Social Security Benefit, multiplied by years of Benefit
Service prior to January 1, 1989
(2) 1.3% of Final Average Earnings plus 0.55% of
Excess Final Average Earnings, multiplied by years of
Benefit Service after December 31, 1988, limited to
35 years
(3) $126 multiplied by years of Benefit Service
Benefit Service was frozen effective October 31, 1994
and earnings were frozen effective December 31, 1994.
Early Retirement
Eligibility Age 55 and ten years of vesting service
Benefit A monthly benefit equal to the normal retirement benefit
reduced by 1/4 of 1% for each month the early
retirement precedes the normal retirement down to age
62 plus 1/2 of 1% for each month thereafter
Vested Termination
Eligibility Five years of vesting service
Benefit The accrued benefit at the date of termination. Reduced
payments may begin any time after eligibility for early
retirement based on the same reductions as early
retirement from active status.

Surviving Spouse
Eligibility Married with five years of vesting service
Benefit A monthly benefit payable to the surviving spouse
beginning at the employee’s earliest retirement age equal
to 50% of the amount payable if the participant had
retired early with a 50% joint and survivor benefit
Normal Form of Annuity
Without Spouse Single life annuity
With Spouse 50% Joint and survivor annuity reduced to be equivalent
to the retirement benefit payable for employee’s lifetime.
Participant receives reduced lifetime benefit and, in
event of participant’s death, 50% of reduced benefit
continues to surviving spouse.
Optional Forms of Annuity Single life annuity
10-year certain and life annuity
100% joint and survivor annuity

50% joint and survivor annuity
Actuarial Equivalence 1971 Unisex Group Annuity Table (85% male, 15%
female) and 8% interest rate
Definitions
Final Average Earnings Average compensation paid for the five consecutive
years during the past ten years which the participant is
employed that produces the highest average.
Compensation after December 31, 1994 is disregarded.
Benefit Service A full year of benefit service is earned if the employee
completes at least 365 days of service. Credit is granted
for fractional years. No benefit service may be earned
after October 31,1994.
Vesting Service A full year of vesting service is earned if the employee
completes at least 365 days of service. Credit is granted
for fractional years.

Definitions
Benefit Service Prior to January 1, 1979: Benefit service equals years and
months of credited service as calculated under prior plan.
After to January 1, 1979: One year of benefit service is
credited if 1,800 or more hours of service are completed.
If under 1,800 hours, then one month is credited for each
150 hours and an additional one month is credited if the
remaining hours are 120 or more.
Benefit service for former Nichols Engineering employees
is credited from July 1, 1978.
Vesting Service Prior to January 1, 1979: The greater of years and months
of credited service as calculated under the previous plan
or one year of vesting service for each year during which
1,000 or more hours were completed.
After January 1, 1979: One year of vesting service
credited on completion of 900 hours or more. Under 900
hours — One month is credited for each 150 hours and an
additional month is credited if the remainder is 120 hours
or more.
Vesting service prior to July 1, 1978 for former employees
of Nichols Engineering — Credited with full years and
months of continuous employment with Nichols
Engineering.
Vesting service prior to July 1, 1978 for Nichols
Engineering employees is credited from date of hire.
Vesting service after July 1, 1978 for these employees is
credited according to the previous paragraph.
Vesting service includes vesting service with the salaried
plan.
Pensionable Pay Total pay
Average Earnings The greater of the average of the highest five
consecutive calendar years of pensionable pay during the
10-year period preceding termination
Normal Retirement Date The first of the month coincident with or next following
attainment of age 65

The salary related formula is as follows:
The monthly benefit for service earned after the effective
date above is equal to 26.25% of average monthly
compensation up to Social Security covered
compensation, plus 47.60% of average monthly
compensation in excess of the Social Security benefit
base, reduced proportionately if benefit service is under
35 years, plus 0.5% of average monthly compensation
multiplied by the number of benefit service years (earned
after the effective date above) in excess of 35 (maximum
five years).
A minimum benefit based on the previous benefit unit
table below times base service (maximum 40 years) will
be paid. Social Security covered compensation is the
average of the taxable wage bases under Social Security
during the 35 years ending with the employee’s Social
Security retirement age.
Average Monthly Compensation Average of the highest five consecutive calendar years
compensation including base salary, bonuses, overtime,
incentive, etc., but excluding other compensation such as
overseas allowances or moving expenses. Compensation
exceeding the IRC section 401(a)(17) limit in the year of
retirement or termination ($200,000 retroactively starting
with the 2002 plan year) will be excluded when the
average monthly compensation is determined.

through the valuation date, most recently by

Eligibility All hourly, bargaining employees at this location will
become plan participants when they are hired. Effective
May 30, 2003, the Forest, OH plant closed. All current
active participants were terminated and future plan
participation was frozen.
Service Years of service and participation are used to determine
the eligibility for benefits and the amount of such
benefits, respectively. Service is credited from date of
hire to Date of Retirement or other termination of
employment.
(1) Years of service prior to July 1, 2000.
Beginning on the effective date, one year shall be
credited for each plan year that the participant has
earned 1,000 hours. If less than 1,000 hours, then
0.1 year credit will be granted for each full 100 hours
of service.
(2) Years of service after July 1, 2000.
One year of service for each 12-month period of
employment with prorated service (to the nearest
one-tenth) for periods less than a full year.
(3) Years of participation prior to July 1, 2000.
Beginning on the effective date, one year shall be
credited for each plan year that the participant has
earned 1,615 hours. If less than 1,615 hours, then
0.1 year credit will be granted for each full 170 hours
of service.
(4) Years of participation after July 1, 2000.
One year of participation for each 12-month period of
employment with prorated service (to the nearest
one-tenth) for periods less than a full year.

Appendix — RMA and TPS Benefits
RMA Benefits (Active Participants) A retiree medical account (RMA) opening balance was
established on the opening balance date for all active
participating employees as of the effective date at RMA
eligible locations. This opening balance was calculated as
follows:
• An annual RMA credit is assumed to be granted to each RMA eligible participant on each December 31
from the RMA accrual date to the opening balance date.
• Each annual RMA credit is accumulated using a 6% annual interest rate from the December 31 date. It
is credited to the opening balance date.
After the establishment of the opening balance, interest
will be credited to the RMA at the end of each month
based on a 6% annual interest rate. These monthly
interest credits will continue until the date of benefit
commencement.
Each eligible participant will also receive an annual RMA
credit on each December 31 as long as the participant
remains an employee. The annual RMA credit, which is
based on the age of the participant at the RMA accrual
date, will be the same annual RMA credit that was used
to determine the opening balance. The RMA accrual date
is generally the participant’s original date of hire or the
credited service date for some acquisitions.
The table below shows the annual RMA credit based on
several sample participant ages on their accrual dates:
Age on RMA Annual
Accrual Date RMA Credit

Schedule SB, line 25 — Change in Method
The funding valuation reflects the following method changes which were approved by the IRS on
June 3, 2025:
● Use of a January 1 Valuation Date for the surviving plan.
● Use of the three segment interest rates using a four-month lookback for the surviving plan.
● Method used to determine the Value of Plan Assets.
Asset Method: Smoothed fair market value of assets over the current and prior two years, adjusted for
contributions, benefit payments, administrative expenses, and expected earnings. The average value is
calculated in this manner is further limited to not less than 90% nor more than 110% of fair market value.
○ As of January 1, 2024, the asset valuation method will be to determine the actuarial value of assets for
the Parker Plan by combining the historical asset values, cash flows, and expected earnings for each
Plan.
○ For any determination dates prior to the merger date, the information will be separately determined for
each of the legacy pre-merger Plans and then totaled.
○ The historical expected earnings for each Plan will be based upon the individual assumed earnings rate
that applied for that Plan (limited to the third segment rate for the Plan Year containing that period).
○ Receivable contributions for each Plan will be discounted based upon the effective interest rate for that
Plan.
● After the mergers, the surviving Plan will maintain all shortfall bases from the disappearing Plans.
Prorated amounts will be reflected for the duration of the post-merger period.
● After the mergers, the surviving Plan will maintain all Funding Standard Carryover Balances ($0) and
Prefunding Balances from the disappearing Plans. The Prefunding Balance for Plan A will be brought
forward with the rate of return on assets for Plan A from May 31, 2022 to January 1, 2023 and then
combined as of January 1, 2023.

The salary related formula is as follows:
The monthly benefit for service earned after the effective
date above is equal to 26.25% of average monthly
compensation up to Social Security covered
compensation, plus 47.60% of average monthly
compensation in excess of the Social Security benefit
base, reduced proportionately if benefit service is under
35 years, plus 0.5% of average monthly compensation
multiplied by the number of benefit service years (earned
after the effective date above) in excess of 35 (maximum
five years).
A minimum benefit based on the previous benefit unit
table below times base service (maximum 40 years) will
be paid. Social Security covered compensation is the
average of the taxable wage bases under Social Security
during the 35 years ending with the employee’s Social
Security retirement age.
Average Monthly Compensation Average of the highest five consecutive calendar years
compensation including base salary, bonuses, overtime,
incentive, etc., but excluding other compensation such as
overseas allowances or moving expenses. Compensation
exceeding the IRC section 401(a)(17) limit in the year of
retirement or termination ($200,000 retroactively starting
with the 2002 plan year) will be excluded when the
average monthly compensation is determined.

Appendix — RMA and TPS Benefits
RMA Benefits (Active Participants) A retiree medical account (RMA) opening balance was
established on the opening balance date for all active
participating employees as of the effective date at RMA
eligible locations. This opening balance was calculated as
follows:
• An annual RMA credit is assumed to be granted to each RMA eligible participant on each December 31
from the RMA accrual date to the opening balance date.
• Each annual RMA credit is accumulated using a 6% annual interest rate from the December 31 date. It
is credited to the opening balance date.
After the establishment of the opening balance, interest
will be credited to the RMA at the end of each month
based on a 6% annual interest rate. These monthly
interest credits will continue until the date of benefit
commencement.
Each eligible participant will also receive an annual RMA
credit on each December 31 as long as the participant
remains an employee. The annual RMA credit, which is
based on the age of the participant at the RMA accrual
date, will be the same annual RMA credit that was used
to determine the opening balance. The RMA accrual date
is generally the participant’s original date of hire or the
credited service date for some acquisitions.
The table below shows the annual RMA credit based on
several sample participant ages on their accrual dates:

Accrual Date RMA Credit

death. This preretirement survivor TPS benefit is payable
until the month prior to the former participant’s sixty-fifth
birthday. If the employee was age 50 or older with five or
more years of service on July 1, 2001 and died after
attaining age 55 with at least 10 years of service, the
preretirement survivor TPS benefit payable to the
surviving spouse continues until the later of the month
prior to the participant’s sixty-fifth birthday or the
surviving spouse’s sixty-fifth birthday.

January 1, 2024 were reflected in the valuation. The multiplier becoming effective during the current plan
year was used in the benefit formula and was considered effective as of the beginning of the plan year, in
accordance with the Pension Protection Act of 2006.
● An increase in the annual maximum benefit limit under IRC section 415 from $265,000 to $275,000.
● An increase in the annual pay limit under IRC Section 401(a)(17) from $330,000 to $345,000.
● A change in the mortality for determining minimum lump sum payments under IRC section 417(e)(3) to the
applicable rates for the current plan year.

Schedule SB, line 25 — Change in Method
The funding valuation reflects the following method changes which were approved by the IRS on
June 3, 2025:
● Use of a January 1 Valuation Date for the surviving plan.
● Use of the three segment interest rates using a four-month lookback for the surviving plan.
● Method used to determine the Value of Plan Assets.
Asset Method: Smoothed fair market value of assets over the current and prior two years, adjusted for
contributions, benefit payments, administrative expenses, and expected earnings. The average value is
calculated in this manner is further limited to not less than 90% nor more than 110% of fair market value.
○ As of January 1, 2024, the asset valuation method will be to determine the actuarial value of assets for
the Parker Plan by combining the historical asset values, cash flows, and expected earnings for each
Plan.
○ For any determination dates prior to the merger date, the information will be separately determined for
each of the legacy pre-merger Plans and then totaled.
○ The historical expected earnings for each Plan will be based upon the individual assumed earnings rate
that applied for that Plan (limited to the third segment rate for the Plan Year containing that period).
○ Receivable contributions for each Plan will be discounted based upon the effective interest rate for that
Plan.
● After the mergers, the surviving Plan will maintain all shortfall bases from the disappearing Plans.
Prorated amounts will be reflected for the duration of the post-merger period.
● After the mergers, the surviving Plan will maintain all Funding Standard Carryover Balances ($0) and
Prefunding Balances from the disappearing Plans. The Prefunding Balance for Plan A will be brought
forward with the rate of return on assets for Plan A from May 31, 2022 to January 1, 2023 and then
combined as of January 1, 2023.
